00:00:53,388 --> 00:00:55,454
narrator: in architectural design,    

4
00:00:55,456 --> 00:00:56,655
exposed wood beams       

5
00:00:56,657 --> 00:00:59,058
use the structural components of a building         

6
00:00:59,060 --> 00:01:00,326
in an aesthetic way.      

7
00:01:00,328 --> 00:01:03,596
these beams are often made of glued laminated timbers.  

8
00:01:03,598 --> 00:01:04,930
they're constructed      

9
00:01:04,932 --> 00:01:07,533
by gluing together several layers of lumber    

10
00:01:07,535 --> 00:01:10,002
and forming them into a particular shape    

11
00:01:10,004 --> 00:01:11,938
such as a curved arch.     

12
00:01:15,142 --> 00:01:19,145
these beams look as though they're a solid piece of wood. 

13
00:01:19,147 --> 00:01:22,080
however, they're actually laminated wood --       

14
00:01:22,082 --> 00:01:25,685
several boards of lumber glued together to form one piece.  

15
00:01:25,687 --> 00:01:28,020
the boards aren't layered haphazardly.  

16
00:01:28,022 --> 00:01:31,157
rather, the top-grade wood goes on the top and bottom,  

17
00:01:31,159 --> 00:01:33,692
where the beam must be the most resistant,  

18
00:01:33,694 --> 00:01:36,228
and lower-grade wood in the middle.         

19
00:01:36,230 --> 00:01:39,231
the boards are far shorter than the finished beam,    

20
00:01:39,233 --> 00:01:41,166
therefore the first step    

21
00:01:41,168 --> 00:01:44,036
is to extend each layer to the required length     

22
00:01:44,038 --> 00:01:47,039
by connecting several boards end to end.          

23
00:01:47,041 --> 00:01:49,241
to do this, a conveyor system 

24
00:01:49,243 --> 00:01:52,177
transports 10 boards at a time to a mill.           

25
00:01:52,179 --> 00:01:55,847
saw blades trim the edges to make them perfectly square, 

26
00:01:55,849 --> 00:01:59,051
then revolving knives cut finger joints on both ends.

27
00:02:08,329 --> 00:02:11,596
when it comes time to connect the boards horizontally,    

28
00:02:11,598 --> 00:02:13,399
the finger joints of one board 

29
00:02:13,401 --> 00:02:15,801
will fit neatly into those of the next.    

30
00:02:17,538 --> 00:02:19,805
the comb-like shape of the finger joints      

31
00:02:19,807 --> 00:02:22,207
creates a far greater service area to glue      

32
00:02:22,209 --> 00:02:25,144
compared to leaving the edges flat.        

33
00:02:25,146 --> 00:02:28,381
more glue makes for a stronger bond between boards.

34
00:02:30,218 --> 00:02:33,351
the glue is high-strength and waterproof.        

35
00:02:33,353 --> 00:02:37,489
it goes on brown but dries translucent.     

36
00:02:37,491 --> 00:02:41,160
workers line up the glued boards
in a machine called a crowder. 

37
00:02:41,162 --> 00:02:44,764
the machine's pressure rollers slide one board into the other,

38
00:02:44,766 --> 00:02:46,999
interlocking the finger joints.

39
00:02:49,370 --> 00:02:52,171
then two plates clamp down on each joint,         

40
00:02:52,173 --> 00:02:54,840
rendering the adjoining boards flush   

41
00:02:54,842 --> 00:02:58,310
should one be sitting slightly higher than the next. 

42
00:02:58,312 --> 00:03:01,714
about 15 seconds of heat cures the glue.        

43
00:03:05,586 --> 00:03:07,519
the connection is barely visible

44
00:03:07,521 --> 00:03:09,755
because the glue dries translucent.       

45
00:03:12,527 --> 00:03:15,060
now that each layer is the required length,    

46
00:03:15,062 --> 00:03:18,531
it's time to adhere them vertically to make the beam.  

47
00:03:18,533 --> 00:03:21,367
first, a glue applicator coats one side.        

48
00:03:24,538 --> 00:03:27,339
then workers turn the layers on their sides 

49
00:03:27,341 --> 00:03:30,209
and stack them in a steel frame
called a jig.         

50
00:03:32,613 --> 00:03:34,012
once they've stacked      

51
00:03:34,014 --> 00:03:37,216
the required number of layers for the beam,         

52
00:03:37,218 --> 00:03:40,018
they activate high-strength steel pressure vices.     

53
00:03:40,020 --> 00:03:42,955
these apply high pressure for six to eight hours     

54
00:03:42,957 --> 00:03:46,125
until the glue between the layers has cured. 

55
00:03:49,696 --> 00:03:52,764
to make an arched beam, it's the same process,     

56
00:03:52,766 --> 00:03:56,102
but they stack then clamp the layers in a curved jig.  

57
00:04:12,052 --> 00:04:13,853
once the glue cures,      

58
00:04:13,855 --> 00:04:18,424
this laminated wood beam is stronger than solid wood.  

59
00:04:26,467 --> 00:04:29,735
however, there are still several more steps to go.   

60
00:04:31,606 --> 00:04:32,938
a two-sided planer       

61
00:04:32,940 --> 00:04:35,941
simultaneously finalizes the dimensions,        

62
00:04:35,943 --> 00:04:38,811
evens out the ends, and removes excess glue    

63
00:04:38,813 --> 00:04:41,480
that oozed out under pressure. 

64
00:04:50,491 --> 00:04:54,093
next, a computer-guided, multi-tool machine       

65
00:04:54,095 --> 00:04:55,761
cuts, drills, and notches the beam      

66
00:04:55,763 --> 00:04:57,096
according to the customer's  

67
00:04:57,098 --> 00:04:59,999
technical drawing specifications.        

68
00:05:04,772 --> 00:05:06,638
then each beam gets a tag   

69
00:05:06,640 --> 00:05:09,508
indicating the order number and part number.        

70
00:05:09,510 --> 00:05:12,311
in the final finishing department,     

71
00:05:12,313 --> 00:05:15,547
workers sand away any visual defects       

72
00:05:15,549 --> 00:05:18,551
and smooth the surface in preparation for staining.  

73
00:05:22,590 --> 00:05:25,991
finishers apply one coat of wood stain with a roller,  

74
00:05:25,993 --> 00:05:28,126
then work it by hand      

75
00:05:28,128 --> 00:05:32,198
to ensure uniform absorption throughout.          

76
00:05:32,200 --> 00:05:35,200
once the beam is shipped to the
construction site,       

77
00:05:35,202 --> 00:05:37,402
the customer might apply a flameproof coating,     

78
00:05:37,404 --> 00:05:39,204
which would significantly slow down           

79
00:05:39,206 --> 00:05:41,073
the rate at which the beam would burn      

80
00:05:41,075 --> 00:05:42,674
in the event of a fire.    

81
00:05:42,676 --> 00:05:45,811
the customer may also stain it a deeper shade         

82
00:05:45,813 --> 00:05:48,214
to match existing woodwork.  

